name: politico
text: Oklahoma entered the world of legal cannabis late, but its hands-off approach launched a boom and a new nickname: ‘Toke-lahoma’ https://t.co/ZCfdChZf6Y

name: politico
text: Oklahoma is now the biggest medical marijuana market in the country on a per capita basis. More than 360,000 Oklahomans—nearly 10 percent of the state’s population—have acquired medical marijuana cards over the last two years. https://t.co/aA6LmKb4rj https://t.co/UyMWzNlbVK

name: politico
text: To meet that demand, Oklahoma has more than 9,000 licensed marijuana businesses, including nearly 2,000 dispensaries and almost 6,000 grow operations https://t.co/aA6LmKb4rj https://t.co/hwidQuuiED

name: politico
text: What is happening in Oklahoma is almost unprecedented among the 35 states that have legalized marijuana in some form since California voters backed medical marijuana in 1996  — in a state that has long stood out for its opposition to drug use https://t.co/aA6LmKb4rj https://t.co/jBBD9FlPrg

name: politico
text: But why? Because cannabis actually bridges socio-economic gaps, expert Chip Baker says. "The only other thing that does it is handguns. All types of people are into firearms. All types of people are into cannabis.” https://t.co/aA6LmKb4rj https://t.co/ywMwkFTRKi

name: politico
text: Indeed, Oklahoma has established arguably the only free-market marijuana industry in the country. Here, there are no limits on how many business licenses can be issued and cities can’t ban marijuana businesses from operating within their borders. https://t.co/aA6LmKb4rj https://t.co/ahFqylC60l
